<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · Built-in grill 120V electrical</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Distinct from gas-side ignition. Marine layer is the silent enemy.</h2>

    <p>Built-in outdoor grills carry a 120V electrical system distinct from the gas-side ignition platform. Rotisserie motor, interior cooking light, backsplash light strip, control panel touch interface, internal junction box wiring, and the GFCI-protected supply circuit all live on the 120V side. Failures here don't affect cooking on most grills, but they affect convenience features customers paid extra for.</p>

    <p>The single biggest factor in 120V failure rates: <strong>LA marine layer condensation.</strong> Coastal grills sit through 200+ marine-layer mornings per year. Humidity infiltrates built-in cabinet enclosures, condenses on 120V terminals overnight, oxidizes copper, corrodes wire insulation. Inland grills don't see the same failure pattern at the same rate.</p>

    <p>This page covers the five common electrical failures, the GFCI-vs-grill diagnostic discipline that catches upstream issues before we quote grill parts, and the honest skip-or-repair conversation we have with owners of year 10+ rotisserie motors.</p>

    <p><strong>$120 outdoor commercial-tier diagnostic, waived with repair.</strong> BHGS #A49573 and EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410). 90-day warranty. Same-day across LA, OC, Ventura. Sister sub-services: <a href="/outdoor/grill-repair/burner-not-igniting/">burner not igniting</a>, <a href="/outdoor/grill-repair/regulator-issues/">regulator issues</a>, <a href="/outdoor/grill-repair/temperature-uneven/">temperature uneven</a>. Parent: <a href="/outdoor/grill-repair/">built-in grill repair pillar</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 ROTISSERIE SKIP-OR-REPAIR (honest framing) -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Rotisserie skip-or-repair on year 10+</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Honest: most owners skip and don't miss it.</h2>

    <p>Rotisserie motor is a luxury accessory, not cooking-critical. The grill cooks normally without it. When the motor fails on a year 10+ unit, the right answer is usually "skip the repair," not "replace the motor."</p>

    <p>The math we walk through with customers:</p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Replacement cost.</strong> $260 to $440 for the motor plus labor.</li>
      <li><strong>Actual usage.</strong> We ask: how many times per year did you use the rotisserie? If the answer is "twice" or "I don't remember," skip the repair. If the answer is "monthly for chickens or pork shoulder," repair.</li>
      <li><strong>Likely remaining service life of the unit.</strong> Year 10 pro-tier grill (Lynx, Fire Magic, Twin Eagles): 5 to 10 more years likely. Year 10 mid-tier: 3 to 5 more years. The motor needs to be used enough times before the grill itself replaces to justify the cost.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>About 70% of year 10+ rotisserie failures result in skip decisions when we lay out the numbers honestly. Customers appreciate not being upsold a repair they don't need. We'd rather you call us next year for the burner work than feel ripped off on rotisserie work you didn't really want.</p>

    <p>Year 5 to 8 rotisserie failures are different: the unit has 7+ more years of life, the motor itself is well within its design service curve, and active rotisserie users miss the feature. Replacement makes sense at that age range.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 TOP 5 CAUSES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Top 5 electrical issues</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">In honest frequency order.</h2>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>1. Interior cooking light bulb (halogen failure)</h3>
      <p>Most common. Halogen bulbs fail at year 4 to 6 and run hot enough to discolor surrounding stainless. We retrofit to LED for the same fixture mount on most Lynx, Fire Magic, Twin Eagles, and DCS models. LED retrofit $80 to $160 vs $90 to $180 OEM halogen replacement; LED lasts 10x longer and runs cool. Same pattern as range-hood LED retrofit.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>2. Rotisserie motor failure (year 5-8 typical, year 10+ skip-or-repair)</h3>
      <p>Sealed motor with internal bearings. Fails from heat exposure, marine-layer humidity infiltration, or simple bearing wear. $260 to $440 replacement. Year 10+ skip conversation per Section 02.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>3. Backsplash LED ribbon (year 5-9 coastal, longer inland)</h3>
      <p>LED ribbon strip illuminating the backsplash area. Marine-layer corrosion accelerates failure on coastal installations. $180 to $340 replacement set, in-line labor.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>4. Control panel touch interface (year 6-10)</h3>
      <p>Capacitive touchscreens (Lynx Smart Grill, Fire Magic Echelon Diamond touch, Hestan Aspire) fail from marine-layer humidity damage. Symptom: buttons unresponsive, ghost touches, partial display. $440 to $780 replacement depending on brand and generation. Pro-tier higher.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>5. Junction box wiring corrosion (year 7-10 coastal)</h3>
      <p>120V junction box inside the built-in cabinetry corrodes from condensation cycles. Copper terminals oxidize, wire insulation degrades. Symptom: intermittent power loss to multiple electrical features at once. $220 to $380 to clean, repair connections, and re-terminate. We use marine-grade heat-shrink and dielectric grease to extend service life.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 GFCI DIAGNOSTIC DISCIPLINE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · GFCI tripping diagnostic discipline</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">~25% of "grill electrical fault" calls are upstream.</h2>

    <p>About 25% of grill electrical service calls turn out to be upstream supply issues, not grill component failures. Customer reports the GFCI breaker tripping when the grill is turned on; assumes the grill is the problem. Often it's a wet outlet, a degraded GFCI breaker, or a backstabbed connection upstream that's been marginal for years and the grill load finally exposed.</p>

    <p>We test the supply first at every electrical diagnostic. The test sequence:</p>
    <ol class="ordered-list">
      <li><strong>Disconnect the grill cord from the outlet.</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Reset the GFCI breaker. Confirm it stays reset with no load.</strong> If it trips with no load on the circuit, the issue is the breaker or upstream wiring; we refer to an electrician.</li>
      <li><strong>Test outlet voltage with a meter.</strong> 120V nominal, no anomalies. Test ground continuity.</li>
      <li><strong>Reconnect the grill, turn on individual loads one at a time</strong> (interior light, then rotisserie, then control panel). Identify which load trips the breaker.</li>
      <li><strong>If a specific grill load trips the breaker</strong>, localize to that component. If the breaker holds with grill loads on, supply is healthy and the original symptom may have been transient or weather-related.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>The $120 diagnostic covers the supply test even when the resolution is upstream. We don't want to install $400 in grill parts and have you call back two weeks later because the actual problem was a wet outlet box.</p>
  </div>
</section>

